## Migration: `TimedExecutor` â†’ .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

This is **Timeout enforcement** â€” a thread is aborted when it exceeds a time limit. The `ThreadAbortException` catch with `ResetAbort` is a defensive guard that kept the thread alive if abort was called externally.

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

- `Thread.Abort()` â†’ throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006)
- `Thread.ResetAbort()` â†’ also throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`
- `ThreadAbortException` â†’ never thrown by the runtime

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(work, timeout, CancellationToken.None);
    }

    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        var token = cts.Token;

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout/cancellation
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### If `work` Is Long-Running and Must Actually Stop

The above only *detaches* from the work on timeout â€” the delegate keeps running in the background. For true cooperative cancellation, pass the token into the work:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers must check the token:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---------|-----------|
| **Work keeps running after timeout** | The `Func<T>` overload only abandons the task â€” it doesn't stop it. Use the `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload and check the token inside `work`. |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` not disposed** | Always `using` the CTS. Leaking it leaks the internal timer from `CancelAfter`. |
| **Blocking calls inside `work` ignore the token** | Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. Use async I/O overloads that accept tokens. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the top level to translate to `TimeoutException`. Let it propagate elsewhere. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If `work` calls code you can't modify, move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` on timeout â€” this is the only true "abort" left in modern .NET. |

---

### Removed APIs Summary

| Old | New |
|-----|-----|
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` / `cts.CancelAfter(timeout)` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed â€” check `token.IsCancellationRequested` if partial continuation is needed |
| Manual `Thread` + `Join` | `Task.Run` + `Task.WaitAsync` |
